Exercise 1a: ggplot basics

Let’s build some plots using data you’ve acquired. Both files included in the Day 5 folder are tab-separated files, so we can use the function read_tsv to import them. They have column names so we need to set col_names to true.

The first file is called rana_stats.txt and is simply the last part of the final Rana ddRAD stats file from iPyrad. Let’s take a look.

# Import data file
stats <- read_tsv(here("data", "Day5_datavis_worksheet_files/rana_stats.txt"), col_names = TRUE)

  1. Make a plot with loci in assembly on the y-axis vs. sample on the x-axis, but make each sample have a point rather than a bar.
ggplot(stats, aes(x = sample_ID, y = loci_in_assembly)) +
  geom_point()

  1. Color each data point by sample ID and remove the x axis labels (by adding the following) because they’re now redundant. theme(axis.title.x=element_blank(), axis.text.x=element_blank(), axis.ticks.x=element_blank())
ggplot(stats, aes(x = sample_ID, y = loci_in_assembly, color = sample_ID)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(axis.title.x = element_blank(), 
        axis.text.x = element_blank(), 
        axis.ticks.x = element_blank())

Exercise 1b: ggplot basics

Let’s take a look at amounts of missing data now. There is another file in the data directory (rana_missing_data.txt) that takes these same samples we’ve been working with and has the number of sites and percentage of missing data.

  1. Import the rana_missing_data.txt file as you did the stats file above and call it missing. Take a look at the file contents.
missing <- read_tsv(here("data", "rana_missing_data.txt"))

ggplot(missing, aes(x = sample_ID, y = percent_missing)) +

Exercise 2: ggtree basics

For ggtree(), we’re going to use the Nexus file that you created from the Day 4 RAxML worksheet. If you haven’t had a chance to do this yet, download the relevant tree files from the data directory on GitHub and go to the part of the 4t_Phylo_tutorial.docx file called “Make a Nexus tree file”.

To recap, this Nexus file should contain the Rana ddRAD tree with support values and branch lengths. Move (or copy) that file to the current working directory. The file should be called ranaddrad_tree.nexus. You can also find it in the data directory on GitHub.

As we discussed in lecture, you need to import the Nexus file as a phylo object, using the ape() package. To do this:

# Import the tree
tree <- read.nexus(here("data", "ranaddrad_tree.nexus"))
# Take a look at the tree to understand the format of a phylo object
tree
## 
## Phylogenetic tree with 12 tips and 10 internal nodes.
## 
## Tip labels:
##   Rneo_T527, Rber_T1113a, Rber_T1113b, Rber_T1114, Rsph_T26064, Rsph_T25870, ...
## Node labels:
##   , 100, 100, 100, 100, 86, ...
## 
## Rooted; includes branch lengths.
# To access the different objects within a phylo object, we can use the dollar sign. What appears when you enter the following?:
tree$Nnode
## [1] 10
  1. How do you take a look at the taxon names of this tree?
tree$tip.label
##  [1] "Rneo_T527"   "Rber_T1113a" "Rber_T1113b" "Rber_T1114"  "Rsph_T26064"
##  [6] "Rsph_T25870" "Rbla_D2865"  "Rbla_D2864"  "Rchi_T2034b" "Rchi_T2034a"
## [11] "Rchi_T2049"  "Rneo_T480"

Run the following code, which builds a tree in ggtree with the absolute minimum amount of labeling.

ggtree(tree)

What does this tree look like? What is it missing? your answer here

  1. Add tip labels to this tree using the geom_tiplab() function within ggtree.
ggtree(tree) +
  geom_tiplab()

  1. You may have noticed that the rooting of this tree is incorrect. We need to reroot the tree before proceeding, but first we need to figure out which node to reroot the tree at (the one that is the common ancestor of all R. chiricahuensis individuals) using its node number. Working off your tree from 2. and using the geom_text() function within ggtree, plot node numbers on the tree you built. You will have to specify the aes.
ggtree(tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_text(aes(label = node))

Which node should you reroot at according to your above tree? your answer here

  1. Now, reroot the tree at the correct node. We can do this using the root() function within ape with the syntax rooted_tree <- root(tree, node=X, edgelabel=TRUE). edgelabel retains the branch lengths.
rooted_tree <- root(tree,
                    node = 21,
                    edgelabel = TRUE)
  1. Rerun the code from 2. but for the new tree. Is the new tree rooted correctly?
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() # yes, tree is now rooted correctly

  1. Working off the tree above, also add on node labels that are the bootstrap support values using the geom_text function within ggtree. The labeling should be label.
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_text(aes(label = label))

  1. There’s a lot going on in the above tree and it’s hard to make out the BS values. Rebuild the tree instead with points at the nodes of the tree (using geom_nodepoint) that are colored according to bootstrap support value. Specify coloring by label (within the aesthetic) and make the size of the points be 2.
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_nodepoint(aes(label = label, color = label), size = 2)

  1. Specify the colors for the bootstrap node points by using the scale_color_manual(values=c("color1", "color2", "color3")) function. There are three different values for the bootstrap support so you’ll need to provide three different color names. Examples of R color names can be found here.
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_nodepoint(aes(label = label, color = label), size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("coral1", "darkblue", "cornflowerblue"))

  1. The legend with the bootstrap colors is obscuring some of your tip labels. We can move the legend around using the exact same function as in normal ggplot(), which is the function theme(). Add on theme(legend.position="bottom")
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_nodepoint(aes(label = label, color = label), size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("coral1", "darkblue", "cornflowerblue")) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom")

  1. Finally, add a scale bar to the plot using the geom_treescale function within ggtree. Save this visualization as plot_tree.
ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  geom_nodepoint(aes(label = label, color = label), size = 2) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("coral1", "darkblue", "cornflowerblue")) +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  geom_treescale()

  1. You can export your tree in a few ways, but we’ll use the ggsave function within ggplot2. This will save the PDF to your current working directory.
ggsave("ranaddrad_tree.pdf", plot_tree)

Advanced exercise

Within ggtree(), we can actually plot other data on top of our existing tree. For example, we can add points on to the tips of our tree and colorize these tip points by percentage of missing data from rana_missing_data.txt from Exercise 1a.

ggtree() uses a special symbol %<+% to add on other data to the tree. The syntax for this is plot_tree %<+% newdata + geomstoadd. However, we actually need to remove the bootstrap support node colors first.

  1. Using your properly rooted phylo object (rooted_tree), build a new tree plot without any information at the nodes (labels or node points). Name this tree_nonodes.
tree_nonodes <-
  ggtree(rooted_tree) +
  geom_tiplab() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  geom_treescale()
  1. Using the missing dataframe, add this on to your existing tree plot (tree_nonodes) and add tip points using geom_tippoint(). Fill the points by percentage missing data and give them a size of 2.
tree_nonodes %<+%
  missing +
  geom_tippoint(aes(color = percent_missing), size = 2)
